{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_70","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"nl -ba docs/pipeline_notes.md | sed -n '80,140p'\"","aggregated_output":"    80\t  a legacy metadata pointer so older consumers can keep reading the prior\n    81\t  sidecar name during migration.\n    82\t- `docs/operator_bundle_design.md` is the authoritative Milestone 6 operator\n    83\t  decision note; later tickets should cite it instead of re-litigating the\n    84\t  default discretization family.\n    85\t\n    86\t### Synapse and coupling handoff contract\n    87\t\n    88\tMilestone 7 now reserves one explicit synapse/coupling discovery surface under\n    89\tthe versioned contract `coupling_bundle.v1`.\n    90\t\n    91\tThe canonical layout is:\n    92\t\n    93\t- `config.paths.processed_coupling_dir/synapse_registry.csv`: local,\n    94\t  simulator-facing synapse registry owned by the library contract\n    95\t- `config.paths.processed_coupling_dir/roots/<root_id>_incoming_anchor_map.npz`:\n    96\t  postsynaptic landing-anchor lookup for one root\n    97\t- `config.paths.processed_coupling_dir/roots/<root_id>_outgoing_anchor_map.npz`:\n    98\t  presynaptic readout-anchor lookup for one root\n    99\t- `config.paths.processed_coupling_dir/roots/<root_id>_coupling_index.json`:\n   100\t  root-local coupling discovery index that can enumerate realized edge bundles\n   101\t- `config.paths.processed_coupling_dir/edges/<pre_root_id>__to__<post_root_id>_coupling.npz`:\n   102\t  canonical edge-level coupling bundle path\n   103\t\n   104\t`config.paths.manifest_json` now also records:\n   105\t\n   106\t- `_coupling_contract_version` and `_coupling_contract` at the manifest header\n   107\t- a per-root `coupling_bundle` block that points to the local synapse registry,\n   108\t  root-local anchor maps, the root-local coupling index, and any explicit\n   109\t  edge-bundle references already built for that root\n   110\t- the design-note path and design-note version each bundle conforms to\n   111\t\n   112\tThe default Milestone 7 semantics are intentionally fixed early:\n   113\t\n   114\t- topology family: `distributed_patch_cloud`\n   115\t- fallback hierarchy: `surface_patch_cloud` ->\n   116\t  `skeleton_segment_cloud` -> `point_neuron_lumped`\n   117\t- sign representation: `categorical_sign_with_signed_weight`\n   118\t- delay representation: `nonnegative_delay_ms_per_synapse_or_delay_bin`\n   119\t- multi-synapse aggregation: `sum_over_synapses_preserving_sign_and_delay_bins`\n   120\t\n   121\t`docs/coupling_bundle_design.md` is the authoritative Milestone 7 decision note;\n   122\tlater tickets should cite it instead of re-litigating the default coupling\n   123\tfamily, fallback hierarchy, or sign/delay/aggregation invariants.\n   124\t\n   125\t### Offline operator QA contract\n   126\t\n   127\tMilestone 6 also now defines one deterministic offline inspection workflow for\n   128\toperator bundles:\n   129\t\n   130\t- `scripts/06_operator_qa.py` reads the local fine operator, coarse operator,\n   131\t  transfer bundle, patch graph, and operator metadata for one or more root IDs\n   132\t- output goes to `config.paths.operator_qa_dir/root-ids-<sorted-root-ids>/`\n   133\t- the report is static: `index.html`, `report.md`, `summary.json`,\n   134\t  per-root detail JSON, and SVG panels for pulse initialization, boundary-mask\n   135\t  inspection, patch decomposition, smoke-evolved fine/coarse fields, and coarse\n   136\t  reconstruction error\n   137\t- the report summary includes pass / warn / fail checks plus an\n   138\t  `operator_readiness_gate` of `go`, `review`, or `hold`\n   139\t- `scripts/07_milestone6_readiness.py` layers a fixture-suite check plus a\n   140\t  manifest/operator-contract audit on top of the operator QA bundle and writes\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_71","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"nl -ba docs/coupling_bundle_design.md | sed -n '1,240p'\"","aggregated_output":"     1\t# Milestone 7 Synapse Asset Contract And Coupling Topology Choice\n     2\t\n     3\tThis note freezes the Milestone 7 synapse and inter-neuron coupling handoff so\n     4\tlater simulator and UI work can target one explicit manifest contract, one\n     5\texplicit bundle layout, and one explicit coupling interpretation.\n     6\t\n     7\t## Contract summary\n     8\t\n     9\tThe processed manifest now carries `_coupling_contract_version:\n    10\tcoupling_bundle.v1` plus a per-root `coupling_bundle` block.\n    11\t\n    12\tThe top-level contract owns:\n    13\t\n    14\t- the authoritative local synapse-registry path\n    15\t- the versioned design-note reference and design-note version\n    16\t- the supported coupling-topology families\n    17\t- the supported fallback modes\n    18\t- the default sign, delay, aggregation, and missing-geometry policies\n    19\t- the canonical root-asset and edge-bundle directories\n    20\t\n    21\tEach per-root `coupling_bundle` block owns:\n    22\t\n    23\t- the same contract and design-note versions\n    24\t- the realized topology family for that root-local handoff\n    25\t- the fallback hierarchy the later mapping/assembly stages must follow\n    26\t- the sign and delay representation rules\n    27\t- the multi-synapse aggregation rule\n    28\t- the discoverable local synapse registry pointer\n    29\t- the incoming and outgoing anchor-map artifact paths\n    30\t- the root-local coupling index path\n    31\t- any explicit edge-level coupling bundle references that already exist\n    32\t\n    33\tThe canonical Milestone 7 layout is:\n    34\t\n    35\t- `config.paths.processed_coupling_dir/synapse_registry.csv`\n    36\t- `config.paths.processed_coupling_dir/roots/<root_id>_incoming_anchor_map.npz`\n    37\t- `config.paths.processed_coupling_dir/roots/<root_id>_outgoing_anchor_map.npz`\n    38\t- `config.paths.processed_coupling_dir/roots/<root_id>_coupling_index.json`\n    39\t- `config.paths.processed_coupling_dir/edges/<pre_root_id>__to__<post_root_id>_coupling.npz`\n    40\t\n    41\tLater tickets may add more sidecars, but those filenames and manifest fields are\n    42\tthe stable discovery surface.\n    43\t\n    44\t## Candidate topology families\n    45\t\n    46\t### Point-to-point\n    47\t\n    48\tDefinition:\n    49\t\n    50\t- each synapse maps to one presynaptic readout anchor and one postsynaptic\n    51\t  landing anchor\n    52\t- the coupling artifact stays close to the raw synapse table\n    53\t\n    54\tAdvantages:\n    55\t\n    56\t- highest localization fidelity\n    57\t- easy to inspect against raw synapse rows\n    58\t- minimal aggregation assumptions\n    59\t\n    60\tCosts:\n    61\t\n    62\t- expensive to evaluate for dense edges\n    63\t- overly sensitive to mesh simplification or anchor jitter\n    64\t- awkward when a later solver runs on patches instead of vertices\n    65\t- does not naturally share one representation across surface, skeleton, and\n    66\t  point-neuron fallbacks\n    67\t\n    68\t### Patch-to-patch\n    69\t\n    70\tDefinition:\n    71\t\n    72\t- each connectome edge becomes one or more direct transfers between coarse patch\n    73\t  IDs\n    74\t- synapse detail is collapsed early into patch-pair weights\n    75\t\n    76\tAdvantages:\n    77\t\n    78\t- cheap to serialize and simulate\n    79\t- easy to compare to coarse point-neuron baselines\n    80\t- naturally aligned with reduced patch-state models\n    81\t\n    82\tCosts:\n    83\t\n    84\t- throws away within-patch landing structure too early\n    85\t- strongly depends on the current patch partition\n    86\t- makes later refinement back to finer resolution difficult\n    87\t- mixes geometric localization and aggregation into one irreversible step\n    88\t\n    89\t### Distributed patch-cloud\n    90\t\n    91\tDefinition:\n    92\t\n    93\t- each synapse or aggregate contributes a sparse cloud over a small set of\n    94\t  presynaptic readout anchors and postsynaptic landing anchors\n    95\t- edge bundles may aggregate multiple synapses, but only after preserving the\n    96\t  cloud structure that records where activity is sampled and where it lands\n    97\t\n    98\tAdvantages:\n    99\t\n   100\t- preserves locality without forcing the simulator to operate on one raw\n   101\t  synapse at a time\n   102\t- works with surface patches now and still degrades cleanly to skeleton or\n   103\t  point-neuron fallbacks\n   104\t- keeps the handoff compatible with both coarse and finer later solvers\n   105\t- separates geometry localization from sign, delay, and weight aggregation\n   106\t\n   107\tCosts:\n   108\t\n   109\t- more metadata than direct patch-to-patch coupling\n   110\t- requires an explicit normalization convention inside each cloud\n   111\t- needs careful testing so aggregation stays deterministic\n   112\t\n   113\t## Decision\n   114\t\n   115\tThe default Milestone 7 coupling topology is `distributed_patch_cloud`.\n   116\t\n   117\tPoint-to-point and patch-to-patch remain recognized comparison families for\n   118\tdebugging, ablations, or future coarse baselines, but the authoritative\n   119\tMilestone 7 handoff assumes that coupling is a sparse cloud-to-cloud transfer\n   120\tderived from synapse-local anchors.\n   121\t\n   122\tWhy this is the default:\n   123\t\n   124\t- it preserves enough geometry to justify morphology-resolved simulation\n   125\t- it avoids binding the later solver to raw per-synapse loops\n   126\t- it keeps one contract usable across mixed morphology classes\n   127\t- it postpones irreversible aggregation until sign, delay, and fallback mode are\n   128\t  already explicit\n   129\t\n   130\t## Fallback hierarchy\n   131\t\n   132\tLater mapping and coupling tickets must follow this hierarchy in order:\n   133\t\n   134\t1. `surface_patch_cloud`\n   135\t2. `skeleton_segment_cloud`\n   136\t3. `point_neuron_lumped`\n   137\t\n   138\tMeaning:\n   139\t\n   140\t- `surface_patch_cloud`: default. Use surface/patch anchors from the Milestone 5\n   141\t  and 6 geometry/operator bundles.\n   142\t- `skeleton_segment_cloud`: fallback when surface geometry is missing or not\n   143\t  trusted but a usable skeleton anchor representation exists.\n   144\t- `point_neuron_lumped`: last resort when only a reduced single-state\n   145\t  representation is available.\n   146\t\n   147\tMissing geometry is never a silent drop. Every mapped synapse or aggregated edge\n   148\tmust either:\n   149\t\n   150\t- record the realized fallback mode explicitly, or\n   151\t- record a structured blocked reason explaining why no supported fallback was\n   152\t  possible\n   153\t\n   154\t## Sign, delay, and aggregation rules\n   155\t\n   156\t### Sign representation\n   157\t\n   158\tMilestone 7 uses `categorical_sign_with_signed_weight`.\n   159\t\n   160\tThat means later bundles must carry both:\n   161\t\n   162\t- an explicit semantic sign label such as excitatory, inhibitory, modulatory, or\n   163\t  unknown\n   164\t- a signed numeric coupling weight or gain term\n   165\t\n   166\tRules:\n   167\t\n   168\t- unknown sign must stay explicit; it may not be silently coerced to positive\n   169\t- opposite signs may not be merged into one net scalar without preserving the\n   170\t  polarity split\n   171\t- downstream consumers should read the categorical field first and treat the\n   172\t  signed numeric field as the magnitude/polarity realization of that label\n   173\t\n   174\t### Delay representation\n   175\t\n   176\tMilestone 7 uses `nonnegative_delay_ms_per_synapse_or_delay_bin`.\n   177\t\n   178\tRules:\n   179\t\n   180\t- delays are serialized in milliseconds\n   181\t- delays must be finite and non-negative\n   182\t- heterogeneous delays on one biological edge may be aggregated into bins, but\n   183\t  not collapsed to one mean value unless the bundle explicitly declares that\n   184\t  approximation\n   185\t\n   186\t### Multi-synapse aggregation\n   187\t\n   188\tMilestone 7 uses `sum_over_synapses_preserving_sign_and_delay_bins`.\n   189\t\n   190\tRules:\n   191\t\n   192\t- aggregate only after grouping by source root, target root, topology family,\n   193\t  realized fallback mode, sign, delay bin, and kernel family\n   194\t- record at least the aggregated synapse count and total signed weight for each\n   195\t  aggregate\n   196\t- never cancel excitatory and inhibitory synapses into one unlabeled total\n   197\t- never merge distinct delay bins into one scalar without an explicit contracted\n   198\t  approximation field\n   199\t\n   200\t## Invariants later milestones must preserve\n   201\t\n   202\tLater simulator, mapping, and UI milestones should preserve these invariants\n   203\tinstead of silently changing them:\n   204\t\n   205\t- the local synapse registry is the auditable row-level source for every anchor\n   206\t  map and edge bundle\n   207\t- root-local anchor maps and edge bundles refer to the same root IDs and the\n   208\t  same design-note version recorded in the manifest\n   209\t- `distributed_patch_cloud` remains the default authoritative family unless a\n   210\t  later contract revision explicitly supersedes this one\n   211\t- fallback mode is an explicit data field, not an inference from missing arrays\n   212\t- a bundle that distributes one coupling event over multiple anchors must state\n   213\t  its normalization convention explicitly in the bundle metadata\n   214\t- sign and delay semantics survive aggregation; later consumers must not assume\n   215\t  that one edge has only one polarity or one delay\n   216\t- missing geometry or mapping failure remains visible as structured metadata, not\n   217\t  as a silent omission from the coupling bundle\n   218\t\n   219\t## Scope boundary\n   220\t\n   221\tThis note freezes the handoff contract, not the final physics kernel. Later\n   222\tMilestone 7 tickets still need to decide the exact coupling kernel family,\n   223\tanchor-mapping payload, and QA checks, but they should cite this note instead of\n   224\tre-litigating the default topology family or the fallback/sign/delay/aggregation\n   225\tsemantics.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
